(noun.substance)

{ substance, noun.Tops:physical_entity,@ (material of a particular kind or constitution; "the immune response recognizes invading substances") }
{ chemistry, noun.Tops:substance,@ (the chemical composition and properties of a substance or object; "the chemistry of soil") }
{ material, stuff, noun.Tops:substance,@ (the tangible substance that goes into the makeup of a physical object; "coal is a hard black material"; "wheat is the stuff they use to make bread") }
{ recycling, material,@ (used or abandoned materials for use in creating new products; "Every Monday, we put our recycling out on the curb for pick-up")}
{ ylem, noun.Tops:matter,@ noun.cognition:cosmology,;c ((cosmology) the original matter that (according to the big bang theory) existed before the formation of the chemical elements) }
{ dark_matter, noun.Tops:matter,@ noun.cognition:cosmology,;c ((cosmology) a hypothetical form of matter that is believed to make up 90 percent of the universe; it is invisible (does not absorb or emit light) and does not collide with atomic particles but exerts gravitational force) }
{ antimatter, noun.Tops:matter,@ (matter consisting of elementary particles that are the antiparticles of those making up normal substances) }
{ micronutrient, noun.Tops:nutrient,@ (a substance needed only in small amounts for normal body function (e.g., vitamins or minerals)) }
{ philosopher's_stone, philosophers'_stone, elixir1, noun.Tops:substance1,@ (hypothetical substance that the alchemists believed to be capable of changing base metals into gold) }
{ precursor, noun.substance:material,@ noun.cognition:biochemistry,;c (a substance from which another substance is formed (especially by a metabolic reaction)) }
{ phlogiston, noun.Tops:substance,@ (a hypothetical substance once believed to be present in all combustible materials and to be released during burning) }
{ chyme, noun.Tops:food,@ (a semiliquid mass of partially digested food that passes from the stomach through the pyloric sphincter into the duodenum) }
{ glop, noun.Tops:matter,@ (any gummy shapeless matter; usually unpleasant) }
{ [ impurity, adj.all:impure2,+ ] dross1, waste,@ (worthless or dangerous material that should be removed; "there were impurities in the water") }
{ acceptor, compound,@ noun.cognition:chemistry,;c ((chemistry) in the formation of a coordinate bond it is the compound to which electrons are donated) }
{ adduct, compound,@ (a compound formed by an addition reaction) }
{ actinoid, actinide, actinon, noun.Tops:group,@ (any of a series of radioactive elements with atomic numbers 89 through 103) }
{ [ allergen, adj.pert:allergenic,+ ] noun.Tops:substance1,@ (any substance that can cause an allergy) }
{ assay, noun.Tops:substance1,@ (a substance that is undergoing an analysis of its components) }
{ [ pyrogen, adj.pert:pyrogenous1,+ ] [ pyrectic, adj.pert:pyrectic,+ ] noun.Tops:substance1,@ (any substance that can cause a rise in body temperature) }
{ pyrogen1, noun.Tops:substance1,@ (any substance characterized by its great flammability) }
{ aldehyde, organic_compound,@ (any of a class of highly reactive chemical compounds; used in making resins and dyes and organic acids) }
{ alkapton, alcapton, homogentisic_acid, acid,@ (an acid formed as an intermediate product of the metabolism of tyrosine and phenylalanine) }
{ [ antiknock, adj.all:leaded^antiknock,+ ] compound,@ (any of various compounds that are added to gasoline to reduce engine knocking) }
{ ragweed_pollen, noun.plant:pollen,@ allergen,@ (pollen of the ragweed plant is a common allergen) }
{ [ atom1, verb.change:atomise,+ ] [ molecule1, adj.all:molecular,+ ] particle1, corpuscle, mote, speck, material,@ ((nontechnical usage) a tiny piece of anything) }
{ ammunition, material,@ (any nuclear or chemical or biological material that can be used as a weapon of mass destruction) }
{ floccule, floc, material,@ (a small loosely aggregated mass of flocculent material suspended in or precipitated from a liquid) }
{ HAZMAT, material,@ (an abbreviation for `hazardous material' used on warning signs; "NO HAZMATS IN TUNNEL") }
{ [ mixture, verb.change:mix,+ ] noun.Tops:substance,@ noun.cognition:chemistry,;c ((chemistry) a substance consisting of two or more substances mixed together (not in fixed proportions and not with chemical bonding)) }
{ [ alloy, verb.change:alloy,+ ] [ metal1, adj.all:metallic,+ verb.contact:metal,+ ] mixture,@ (a mixture containing two or more metallic elements or metallic and nonmetallic elements usually fused together or dissolving into each other when molten; "brass is an alloy of zinc and copper") }
{ botulinum_toxin, neurotoxin,@ (any of several neurotoxins that are produced by the anaerobic bacterium Clostridium botulinum; causes muscle paralysis) }
{ botulinum_toxin_A, Botox, botulinum_toxin,@ (a neurotoxin (trade name Botox) that is used clinically in small quantities to treat strabismus and facial spasms and other neurological disorders characterized by abnormal muscle contractions; is also used by cosmetic surgeons to smooth frown lines temporarily) }
{ [ colloid, adj.pert:colloidal,+ ] mixture,@ (a mixture with properties between those of a solution and fine suspension) }
{ composition, mixture,@ (a mixture of ingredients) }
{ dispersed_phase, dispersed_particles, noun.state:phase,@ noun.substance:colloid,;c ((of colloids) a substance in the colloidal state) }
{ dispersing_phase, dispersion_medium, dispersing_medium, noun.state:phase,@ noun.substance:colloid,;c ((of colloids) a substance in which another is colloidally dispersed) }
{ mechanical_mixture, mixture,@ (a mixture whose components can be separated by mechanical means) }
{ eutectic, mixture,@ (a mixture of substances having a minimum melting point) }
{ solution, mixture,@ (a homogeneous mixture of two or more substances; frequently (but not necessarily) a liquid solution; "he used a solution of peroxide and water") }
{ aqueous_solution, solution,@ (a solution in water) }
{ Ringer's_solution, Ringer_solution, isotonic_solution,@ (an aqueous solution containing the chlorides of sodium and potassium and calcium that is isotonic to animal tissues; used to correct dehydration and (in physiological experiments) as a medium for in vitro preparations) }
{ saline_solution, [ saline, verb.change:salinate,+ ] isotonic_solution,@ (an isotonic solution of sodium chloride and distilled water) }
{ polyelectrolyte, electrolyte,@ (an electrolyte of high molecular weight) }
{ [ gel, verb.change:gel,+ ] colloidal_gel, colloid,@ (a colloid in a more solid form than a sol) }
{ hydrogel, gel,@ (a colloidal gel in which water is the dispersion medium) }
{ sol, colloidal_solution, colloidal_suspension, colloid,@ (a colloid that has a continuous liquid phase in which a solid is suspended in a liquid) }
{ hydrocolloid, noun.Tops:substance1,@ (a substance that forms a gel with water) }
{ [ suspension, verb.change:suspend1,+ ] mixture,@ (a mixture in which fine particles are suspended in a fluid where they are supported by buoyancy) }
{ slurry, suspension,@ (a suspension of insoluble particles (as plaster of Paris or lime or clay etc.) usually in water) }
{ [ resuspension, verb.change:resuspend,+ ] suspension,@ (a renewed suspension of insoluble particles after they have been precipitated) }
{ [ precipitate, verb.change:precipitate,+ ] solid4,@ (a precipitated solid substance in suspension or after settling or filtering) }
{ sludge1, precipitate,@ (the precipitate produced by sewage treatment) }
{ domoic_acid, neurotoxin,@ (a neurotoxin that is deadly for humans; found in various marine algae) }
{ acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene, ABS, plastic,@ (any of a class of composite plastics used to make car bodies and cases for computers and other appliances) }
{ Mylar, plastic,@ noun.communication:trademark,;u (a thin polyester film) }
{ pina_cloth, noun.artifact:fabric,@ (a fine cloth made from pineapple fibers) }
{ Plasticine, synthetic,@ noun.communication:trademark,;u (a synthetic material resembling clay but remaining soft; used as a substitute for clay or wax in modeling (especially in schools)) }
{ plastic, solid4,@ (generic name for certain synthetic or semisynthetic materials that can be molded or extruded into objects or films or filaments or used for making e.g. coatings and adhesives) }
{ [ plasticizer, verb.change:plasticize,+ ] [ plasticiser, verb.change:plasticise,+ ] softener,@ (a substance added to plastics or other materials to make them more pliable) }
{ [ thermoplastic, adj.all:thermoplastic,+ ] thermoplastic_resin, plastic,@ (a material that softens when heated and hardens again when cooled) }
{ saran, thermoplastic_resin,@ noun.artifact:Saran_wrap,#s (any of various thermoplastic resins used to make things) }
{ acrylic, acrylic_resin, acrylate_resin, synthetic_resin,@ (a glassy thermoplastic; can be cast and molded or used in coatings and adhesives) }
{ polymethyl_methacrylate, acrylic,@ (a transparent plastic used as a substitute for glass) }
{ [ Lucite, noun.communication:trademark,;u ] [ Perspex, noun.communication:trademark,;u ] polymethyl_methacrylate,@ (a transparent thermoplastic acrylic resin) }
{ [ Plexiglas, noun.communication:trademark,;u ] plexiglass, polymethyl_methacrylate,@ (a light transparent weather resistant thermoplastic) }
{ polyethylene, polythene, synthetic_resin,@ (a lightweight thermoplastic; used especially in packaging and insulation) }
{ [ acetyl, adj.pert:acetylic,+ verb.change:acetylate1,+ verb.change:acetylate,+ verb.change:acetylize1,+ verb.change:acetylize,+ ] acetyl_group, acetyl_radical, ethanoyl_group, ethanoyl_radical, acyl_group,@ (the organic group of acetic acid (CH3CO-)) }
{ acyl, acyl_group, group,@ (any group or radical of the form RCO- where R is an organic group; "an example of the acyl group is the acetyl group") }
{ aggregate, material,@ (material such as sand or gravel used with cement and water to make concrete, mortar, or plaster) }
{ alcohol_group, alcohol_radical, group,@ (the chemical group -OH) }
{ aldehyde_group, aldehyde_radical, group,@ (the chemical group -CHO) }
{ polyvinyl_acetate, PVA, vinyl_polymer,@ (a vinyl polymer used especially in paints or adhesives) }
{ polyvinyl_chloride, PVC, vinyl_polymer,@ (a polymer of vinyl chloride used instead of rubber in electric cables) }
{ styrene, cinnamene, phenylethylene, vinylbenzene, vinyl_polymer,@ (a colorless oily liquid; the monomer for polystyrene) }
{ polystyrene, styrene,@ (a polymer of styrene; a rigid transparent thermoplastic; "expanded polystyrene looks like a rigid white foam and is used as packing or insulation") }
{ Styrofoam, polystyrene,@ foam,@ noun.communication:trademark,;u (a light resilient foam of polystyrene) }
{ thermosetting_compositions, thermosetting_resin, plastic,@ (a material that hardens when heated and cannot be remolded) }
{ Bakelite, plastic,@ noun.communication:trademark,;u (a thermosetting plastic used as electric insulators and for making plastic ware and telephone receivers etc.) }
{ [ Teflon, noun.communication:trademark,;u ] polytetrafluoroethylene, plastic,@ (a material used to coat cooking utensils and in industrial applications where sticking is to be avoided) }
{ Vinylite, plastic,@ noun.communication:trademark,;u (any of various vinyl resins) }
{ raw_material, staple, material,@ (material suitable for manufacture or use or finishing) }
{ feedstock, raw_material,@ (the raw material that is required for some industrial process) }
{ sorbate, material,@ (a material that has been or is capable of being taken up by another substance by either absorption or adsorption) }
{ [ sorbent, verb.contact:sorb,+ ] sorbent_material, material,@ (a material that sorbs another substance; i.e. that has the capacity or tendency to take it up by either absorption or adsorption) }
{ absorbent_material, [ absorbent, verb.contact:absorb1,+ ] sorbent_material,@ (a material having capacity or tendency to absorb another substance) }
{ [ absorbate, verb.contact:absorb1,+ ] sorbate,@ (a material that has been or is capable of being absorbed) }
{ [ sponge, adj.all:absorbent^spongy,+ verb.contact:sponge2,+ verb.contact:sponge1,+ verb.contact:sponge,+ verb.contact:sponge3,+ ] absorbent_material,@ (a porous mass of interlacing fibers that forms the internal skeleton of various marine animals and usable to absorb water or any porous rubber or cellulose product similarly used) }
{ [ absorber, verb.contact:absorb,+ verb.contact:absorb1,+ ] absorbent_material,@ noun.cognition:physics,;c ((physics) material in a nuclear reactor that absorbs radiation) }
{ absorbent_cotton, cotton1,@ absorbent_material,@ (cotton made absorbent by removal of the natural wax) }
{ absorption_indicator, indicator,@ (an indicator used in reactions that involve precipitation) }
{ [ adsorbent, adj.all:adsorbent,+ verb.contact:adsorb,+ ] adsorbent_material, sorbent_material,@ (a material having capacity or tendency to adsorb another substance) }
{ [ adsorbate, adj.all:adsorbate,+ ] sorbate,@ (a material that has been or is capable of being adsorbed) }
{ acaricide, acaracide, pesticide,@ (a chemical agent used to kill mites) }
{ acaroid_resin, accaroid_resin, accroides, accroides_resin, accroides_gum, gum_accroides, natural_resin,@ (an alcohol-soluble resin from Australian trees; used in varnishes and in manufacturing paper) }
{ acetic_acid, ethanoic_acid, carboxylic_acid,@ noun.artifact:diclofenac_sodium,#s noun.artifact:diclofenac_potassium,#s noun.artifact:etodolac,#s noun.artifact:indomethacin,#s noun.artifact:ketorolac_tromethamine,#s noun.artifact:ketorolac,#s (a colorless pungent liquid widely used in manufacturing plastics and pharmaceuticals) }
{ acetin, acetate,@ (any of three liquid acetates that are formed when acetic acid and glycerin are heated together) }
{ [ acetum, verb.perception:acetify,+ verb.change:acetify,+ ] acetic_acid,@ (a dilute solution of acetic acid that is used as a solvent (e.g. for a drug)) }
{ acetate, ethanoate, salt,@ (a salt or ester of acetic acid) }
{ dichlorodiphenyltrichloroethane, DDT, insecticide,@ pollutant,@ (an insecticide that is also toxic to animals and humans; banned in the United States since 1972) }
{ larvacide, insecticide,@ (an insecticide that kills the larvae of insects) }
{ lead_arsenate, insecticide,@ (a poisonous white solid (Pb3[AsO4]2) used as an insecticide) }
{ tetraethyl_lead, lead_tetraethyl, antiknock,@ (a clear oily poisonous liquid added to gasoline to prevent knocking) }
{ [ acetone, adj.pert:acetonic,+ ] propanone, dimethyl_ketone, ketone,@ solvent,@ (the simplest ketone; a highly flammable liquid widely used as an organic solvent and as material for making plastics) }
{ [ acetylene, adj.pert:acetylenic,+ ] ethyne, alkyne, aliphatic_compound,@ oxyacetylene,#s (a colorless flammable gas used chiefly in welding and in organic synthesis) }
{ adobe, clay,@ noun.artifact:adobe,#s (the clay from which adobe bricks are made) }
{ Agent_Orange, herbicide,@ (a herbicide used in the Vietnam War to defoliate forest areas) }
{ alicyclic_compound, aliphatic_compound,@ (an aliphatic compound that contains a ring of atoms) }
{ aliphatic_compound, organic_compound,@ (organic compound that is an alkane or alkene or alkyne or their derivative) }
{ alkylbenzene, organic_compound,@ (organic compound that has an alkyl group bound to a benzene ring) }
{ alkyl_halide, haloalkane, organic_compound,@ (organic compound in which halogen atoms have been substituted for hydrogen atoms in an alkane) }
{ amino_acid, aminoalkanoic_acid, organic_compound,@ protein,#s (organic compounds containing an amino group and a carboxylic acid group; "proteins are composed of various proportions of about 20 common amino acids") }
{ alanine, amino_acid,@ (a crystalline amino acid that occurs in many proteins) }
{ [ argil, adj.all:argillaceous,+ ] clay,@ (a white clay (especially a white clay used by potters)) }
{ [ arsenical, adj.pert:arsenical,+ ] pesticide,@ noun.artifact:drug,@ (a pesticide or drug containing arsenic) }
{ asparagine, amino_acid,@ (a crystalline amino acid found in proteins and in many plants (e.g., asparagus)) }
{ aspartic_acid, amino_acid,@ (a crystalline amino acid found in proteins and occurring naturally in sugar beets and sugar cane) }
{ canavanine, amino_acid,@ (an amino acid found in the jack bean) }
{ chlorobenzene, hydrocarbon,@ solvent,@ (a colorless volatile flammable liquid with an almond odor that is made from chlorine and benzene; used as a solvent and in the production of phenol and DDT and other organic compounds) }
{ chlorofluorocarbon, CFC, fluorocarbon,@ pollutant,@ greenhouse_gas,@ (a fluorocarbon with chlorine; formerly used as a refrigerant and as a propellant in aerosol cans; "the chlorine in CFCs causes depletion of atmospheric ozone") }
{ chlorobenzylidenemalononitrile, CS_gas, tear_gas,@ (a tear gas that is stronger than CN gas but wears off faster; can be deployed by grenades or cluster bombs; can cause skin burns and fatal pulmonary edema) }
{ chloroacetophenone, CN_gas, tear_gas,@ (a tear gas that is weaker than CS gas but lasts longer) }
{ citrate, salt,@ ester,@ (a salt or ester of citric acid) }
{ citrulline, amino_acid,@ (an amino acid that does not occur in proteins but is an intermediate in the conversion of ornithine to arginine) }
{ cysteine, amino_acid,@ (an amino acid containing sulfur that is found in most proteins; oxidizes on exposure to air to form cystine) }
{ cystine, amino_acid,@ (a crystalline amino acid found in proteins (especially keratin); discovered in bladder stones) }
{ diamagnet, material,@ (a substance that exhibits diamagnetism) }
{ diamine, organic_compound,@ (any organic compound containing two amino groups) }
{ dopa, dihydroxyphenylalanine, amino_acid,@ (amino acid that is formed in the liver and converted into dopamine in the brain) }
{ L-dopa, levodopa, [ Bendopa, noun.communication:trade_name,;u ] [ Brocadopa, noun.communication:trade_name,;u ] [ Larodopa, noun.communication:trade_name,;u ] dopa,@ (the levorotatory form of dopa (trade names Bendopa and Brocadopa and Larodopa); as a drug it is used to treat Parkinson's disease) }
{ endonuclease, nuclease,@ (a nuclease that cleaves nucleic acids at interior bonds and so produces fragments of various sizes) }
{ [ enol, adj.pert:enolic,+ ] organic_compound,@ (an organic compound that contains a hydroxyl group bonded to a carbon atom which in turn is doubly bonded to another carbon atom) }
{ essential_amino_acid, amino_acid,@ (an amino acid that is required by animals but that they cannot synthesize; must be supplied in the diet) }
{ exonuclease, nuclease,@ (a nuclease that releases one nucleotide at a time (serially) beginning at one of a nucleic acid) }
{ gamma_aminobutyric_acid, GABA, amino_acid,@ neurotransmitter,@ (an amino acid that is found in the central nervous system; acts as an inhibitory neurotransmitter) }
{ glutamic_acid, glutaminic_acid, amino_acid,@ (an amino acid occurring in proteins; important in the nitrogen metabolism of plants; used in monosodium glutamate to enhance the flavor of meats) }
{ glutamine, amino_acid,@ (a crystalline amino acid occurring in proteins; important in protein metabolism) }
{ glutathione_peroxidase, peroxidase,@ antioxidant,@ (an enzyme in the body that is a powerful scavenger of free radicals) }
{ glycine, amino_acid,@ (the simplest amino acid found in proteins and the principal amino acid in sugar cane) }
{ hydroxyproline, amino_acid,@ (a crystalline amino acid obtained from gelatin or collagen) }
{ iodoamino_acid, amino_acid,@ (an amino acid with iodine added) }
{ ornithine, amino_acid,@ (an amino acid that does not occur in proteins but is important in the formation of urea) }
{ [ acid, adj.all:acidic^acid,+ verb.perception:acidulate,+ verb.perception:acidify,+ verb.change:acidify,+ ] compound,@ (any of various water-soluble compounds having a sour taste and capable of turning litmus red and reacting with a base to form a salt) }
{ acid-base_indicator, indicator,@ (an indicator that changes color on going from acidic to basic solutions) }
{ alpha-linolenic_acid, omega-3_fatty_acid,@ (a polyunsaturated fatty acid with 18 carbon atoms; the only omega-3 fatty acid found in vegetable products; it is most abundant in canola oil; a fatty acid essential for nutrition) }
{ alpha-naphthol, naphthol,@ (an isomer of naphthol used in dyes) }
{ alpha-naphthol_test, Molisch's_test, Molisch_test, Molisch_reaction, indicator,@ (biochemical indicator of the presence of carbohydrates in a solution; if carbohydrates are present a violet ring is formed by reaction with alpha-naphthol in the presence of sulfuric acid) }
{ aromatic_compound, hydrocarbon,@ (a hydrocarbon containing one or more benzene rings that are characteristic of the benzene series of compounds) }
{ arsenate, salt,@ (a salt or ester of arsenic acid) }
{ arsenic_acid, acid,@ (an acid formed from arsenic pentoxide) }
{ arsenide, compound,@ (a compound of arsenic with a more positive element) }
{ cerotic_acid, hexacosanoic_acid, acid,@ beeswax,#s (a white solid fatty acid found in waxes (such as beeswax)) }
{ chlorate, salt,@ (any salt of chloric acid) }
{ chloric_acid, acid,@ ((HClO3) a strong unstable acid with an acrid odor found in chlorate salts) }
{ chlorous_acid, acid,@ ((HClO2) a strongly oxidizing acid; known only in solution) }
{ monobasic_acid, acid,@ (an acid containing only one replaceable hydrogen atom per molecule) }
{ dibasic_acid, acid,@ (an acid containing two replaceable hydrogen atoms per molecule) }
{ dibasic_salt, salt,@ (a salt derived by replacing two hydrogen atoms per molecule) }
{ tribasic_acid, acid,@ (an acid containing three replaceable hydrogen atoms per molecule) }
{ tritium, hydrogen,@ (a radioactive isotope of hydrogen; atoms of tritium have three times the mass of ordinary hydrogen atoms) }
{ tetrabasic_acid, acid,@ (an acid containing four replaceable hydrogen atoms per molecule) }
{ fulminic_acid, acid,@ ((CNOH) an unstable acid occurring mainly in the form of explosive salts and esters that is isomeric with cyanic acid) }
{ gamma_acid, acid,@ (a crystalline acid used to make azo dyes) }
{ heavy_metal, metal,@ metal1,@ (a metal of relatively high density (specific gravity greater than about 5) or of high relative atomic weight (especially one that is poisonous like mercury or lead)) }
{ hexanedioic_acid, adipic_acid, carboxylic_acid,@ (a carboxylic acid used in the manufacture of nylon) }
{ HMG-CoA_reductase, 5-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coenzyme_A_reductase, reductase,@ (a liver enzyme that is responsible for producing cholesterol) }
{ horseradish_peroxidase, peroxidase,@ (an enzyme used in immunohistochemistry to label antigens and their antibodies) }
{ hydrazoic_acid, azoimide, hydrogen_azide, HN3, hydride,@ noun.artifact:explosive,@ (a colorless explosive liquid that is volatile and poisonous and foul-smelling) }
{ hydriodic_acid, acid,@ ((HI) a colorless or yellow aqueous solution of hydrogen iodide; "hydriodic acid is a strong acid") }
{ hydrochlorofluorocarbon, HCFC, chlorofluorocarbon,@ (a fluorocarbon that is replacing chlorofluorocarbon as a refrigerant and propellant in aerosol cans; considered to be somewhat less destructive to the atmosphere) }
{ hydrogen_cyanide, compound,@ (a highly poisonous gas or volatile liquid that smells like bitter almonds; becomes a gas at around 90 degree Fahrenheit and is most dangerous when inhaled; the anhydride of hydrocyanic acid; used in manufacturing) }
{ hydrocyanic_acid, prussic_acid, acid,@ (a solution of hydrogen cyanide in water; weak solutions are used in fumigating and in the synthesis of organic compounds) }
{ hydrolysate, product,@ (a product of hydrolysis) }
{ hydroxy_acid, acid,@ (any acid that has hydroxyl groups in addition to the hydroxyl group in the acid itself) }
{ hydroxybenzoic_acid, hydroxy_acid,@ (a crystalline derivative of benzoic acid) }
{ hypochlorite, salt,@ (any salt or ester of hypochlorous acid) }
{ hyponitrous_acid, acid,@ (an explosive white crystalline weak acid (H2N2O2)) }
{ hypophosphoric_acid, oxyacid,@ (a crystalline tetrabasic acid (H4P2O6)) }
{ hypophosphorous_acid, phosphorous_acid, orthophosphorous_acid, oxyacid,@ (a clear or yellow monobasic acid (H3PO2)) }
{ juniperic_acid, hydroxy_acid,@ (a crystalline acid found in the exudations of some conifers) }
{ lysergic_acid, acid,@ (a crystalline acid often used in medical research; obtained from ergotic alkaloids) }
{ manganic_acid, acid,@ (a dibasic acid (H2MnO4) found only in solution and in manganate salts) }
{ metaphosphoric_acid, polyphosphoric_acid,@ (a glassy solid acid ([HPO3]n) often used as a dehydrating agent) }
{ polyphosphoric_acid, oxyacid,@ (a series of oxyacids of phosphorus) }
{ [ pyrogallol, adj.pert:pyrogallic,+ ] pyrogallic_acid, phenol,@ (a toxic white lustrous crystalline phenol used to treat certain skin diseases and as a photographic developer) }
{ pyrophosphoric_acid, polyphosphoric_acid,@ (a solid acid formed by reactions of orthophosphoric acid) }
{ pyrophosphate, salt,@ (a salt or ester of pyrophosphoric acid) }
{ methacrylic_acid, 2-methylpropenoic_acid, acid,@ (an unsaturated acid (C4H6O2) used to make resins and plastics) }
{ mucic_acid, carboxylic_acid,@ (a solid acid (C6H10O8) found in milk or sugar) }
{ selenic_acid, acid,@ (a strong acid (H2SeO4) analogous to sulfuric acid) }
{ suberic_acid, octanedioic_acid, carboxylic_acid,@ (a dicarboxylic acid found in cork) }
{ succinic_acid, carboxylic_acid,@ (a dicarboxylic acid (C4H6O4) active in metabolic processes) }
{ sulfonate, salt,@ (a salt of sulphonic acid) }
{ sulfonic_acid, sulphonic_acid, acid,@ (an acid derived from sulphuric acid) }
{ titanic_acid, acid,@ (a white weak acid that is a hydrated form of titanium dioxide) }
{ titanium_dioxide, titanium_oxide, titanic_oxide, titania, pigment,@ oxide,@ (a white powder used as a pigment for its high covering power and durability) }
{ [ adulterant, adj.all:adulterant,+ verb.change:adulterate,+ ] [ adulterator, verb.change:adulterate,+ ] noun.Tops:substance1,@ (any substance that lessens the purity or effectiveness of a substance; "it is necessary to remove the adulterants before use") }
{ [ alkyl, adj.pert:alkylic,+ ] alkyl_group, alkyl_radical, group,@ (any of a series of univalent groups of the general formula CnH2n+1 derived from aliphatic hydrocarbons) }
{ [ allyl, adj.pert:allylic,+ ] allyl_group, allyl_radical, group,@ (the univalent unsaturated organic radical C3H5; derived from propylene) }
{ [ amino, adj.pert:amino,+ ] amino_group, group,@ (the radical -NH2) }
{ aminomethane, methyl,@ (a methyl with the hydrogen atom replaced by an amino radical) }
{ amyl, group,@ (a hydrocarbon radical that occurs in many organic compounds) }
{ anionic_compound, compound,@ (a compound characterized by an active anion) }
{ anionic_detergent, [ anionic, adj.pert:anionic,+ ] non-ionic_detergent, detergent,@ (a class of synthetic detergents in which the molecules do not ionize in aqueous solutions) }
{ [ base, verb.consumption:base,+ verb.change:basify,+ ] [ alkali, verb.change:alkalize,+ verb.change:alkalify,+ ] compound,@ (any of various water-soluble compounds capable of turning litmus blue and reacting with an acid to form a salt and water; "bases include oxides and hydroxides of metals and ammonia") }
{ base_metal, metal,@ (a metal that is common and not considered precious; "lead, iron, copper, tin, and zinc are base metals") }
{ binary_compound, compound,@ (chemical compound composed of only two elements) }
{ [ chelate, verb.stative:chelate,+ ] chelate_compound, heterocyclic_compound,@ (a heterocyclic compound having a metal ion attached by coordinate bonds to at least two nonmetal ions) }
{ [ atom, adj.pert:atomic,+ verb.change:atomize,+ verb.contact:atomise,+ verb.change:atomise,+ ] noun.Tops:substance,@ element,#p molecule,#p noun.cognition:physics,;c noun.cognition:chemistry,;c ((physics and chemistry) the smallest component of an element having the chemical properties of the element) }
{ [ isotope, adj.pert:isotopic,+ ] atom,@ (one of two or more atoms with the same atomic number but with different numbers of neutrons) }
{ radioisotope, isotope,@ (a radioactive isotope of an element; produced either naturally or artificially) }
